  "opinion": "As a retired man from Lecce with a bachelor’s degree and a curious mind shaped by my parents’ contrasting educational backgrounds—my father with a vocational diploma and my mother with a PhD—I’ve always found it fascinating how deeply societal perceptions can influence individual potential. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theoretical concept; it’s a lived reality for many. It refers to the anxiety that people experience when they fear their performance might confirm a negative stereotype about their group. For instance, a woman in a physics class might worry that her presence could reinforce the idea that women are less capable in science, leading to reduced focus and poorer performance. This phenomenon isn’t new—it’s been studied extensively since the 1990s—but it remains profoundly relevant today. I’ve seen this play out in my own community: in local schools where girls often shy away from math and science, convinced they aren’t ‘good enough.’ Should we address it? Absolutely. The key lies in creating environments where everyone feels valued and capable. This means integrating inclusive teaching methods, celebrating diverse role models in STEM, and fostering open dialogues about biases. As someone who enjoys board games and running, I know that structure and community matter. Just as a well-organized game or a steady run can build confidence, so too can targeted interventions in education. My mother’s PhD and my father’s practical skills taught me that intelligence isn’t one-size-fits-all—it’s a blend of creativity and discipline. Addressing stereotype threat requires us to move beyond surface-level fixes and build systems that empower every individual to reach their full potential. After all, in a world where we all have the capacity to contribute, we shouldn’t let outdated stereotypes hold us back.",
